---
description: Omni-channel communication (Twilio, email, Slack/Teams, WebSocket)
globs: backend/integrations/**, backend/services/channels/**, backend/api/routes/channels/**
---

Channel stack:
- Twilio for WhatsApp and SMS (required).
- Configurable email provider (e.g. SendGrid, AWS SES) for ticket ingestion and outbound email.
- Slack / Microsoft Teams integration for agent workflows and notifications.
- WebSocket for live website chat and real-time streaming.
- Optional: social media, mobile app (API-first).

Omni-channel rules:
- Unified conversation thread: one logical conversation may have messages from multiple channels (chat, email, WhatsApp, etc.); store channel per message and allow channel switching without losing context.
- Conversation history synchronization: persist all messages in a canonical store (Supabase); sync state for real-time clients via WebSocket or polling.
- Isolate channel adapters behind a common interface (e.g. ChannelProvider, send_message, receive_webhook) so business logic does not depend on a specific provider.
- Incoming webhooks (Twilio, email inbound, Slack events) must validate signatures/tokens and route to a single ingestion pipeline that creates/updates conversations and messages.
- Do not hardcode Twilio credentials or email API keys; use configuration and env.

Twilio-specific:
- Use Twilio SDK for sending/receiving WhatsApp and SMS; handle delivery status callbacks and store in conversation history.
- Implement idempotency where possible for webhook handlers to avoid duplicate message processing.
- Rate limiting and validation on webhook endpoints to prevent abuse.

Do not:
- Put channel-specific logic (e.g. Twilio XML) in core conversation or ticket services.
- Assume a single channel per conversation; design for multi-channel from the start.
